ions were academically stratified, providing limited opportunities for a chosen few while leaving the majority of students in segregated, underperforming schools. Nevertheless, desegregation did provide a transformative opportunity for those students involved. While desegregation was the external impetus that brought students together, the students themselves made integration possible, and many students found that the few years that they spent in these schools had a profound impact on broadening their understanding of different racial and ethnic groups. In very real ways, desegregated schools reduced racial isolation for those who took part.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAfrican American childrenxEducationzIllinoiszChicagoxHistory. 0aHigh school graduateszIllinoiszChicago. 0aPublic schoolszIllinoiszChicagoxHistory. 0aSchool integrationzIllinoiszChicagoxHistory. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  aEducation, Race, Ethnic Studies, Discrimination, Race Relations, History, 20th Century, Social Science, courts, federal government, desegregation, Black schools, students, Chicago high schools, segregated, underperforming schools, racia, ethnic groups, racial isolation, 1988, academy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073913840uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197881009940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn